{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d6b374d3-bfbf-421f-9e17-62e4aa0ea37f","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, grab the single-file build from the [diagnostics repo releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics).\n- For flame-graph style analysis without copying the file off the pod, use `dotnet-trace collect --format speedscope` then open it at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n- To copy the trace out: `kubectl cp <pod>:<path-to-trace> ./trace.nettrace`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d94ff68f-02a1-4e71-810f-90d3ea03b8f5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":335,"requestId":"1B88:2FFBCA:D3FD44:F0BFB5:6A0281D5"},"id":"c883a6f3-2a49-40c6-8e7a-ca3336eeff2b","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:26:54.493Z","parentId":"35387709-0994-4481-9ec3-acab5bf21ab8"}
